@aayushs0598 DuPont is always true. If additional borrowing doesn't add net income, it will reduce the asset turnover ratio.
@aayushs0598 Difference is just of Maths. The purpose is to explain how much of the assets are funded by debt & equity.

What is DuPont Analysis?  RoE = Profitability x Productivity x Financial Leverage   Profitability = Net Profit/Sales  Productivity = Sales/Total Assets Financial Leverage = Total Assets/Total Equity  In nutshell, RoE = Net Profit Margin x Asset Turnover Ratio x Equity Multiplier

Now, what is beta? Mathematically, it's volatility of stock as compared to volatility of market. But practically, it means risk. Say if co. increases financial risk by borrowing debt, then beta shoots up and eventually, COE.  FYI, COD = (Interest outflow) x (1-tax)  (4/4)

Generally, it‚Äôs understood that COE is the dividend cost. But, practically, it‚Äôs not. Let‚Äôs understand: COE = rf + Beta (rm ‚Äì rf) where, rf  = Risk free return (we can take SBI‚Äôs FD rate)              rm = Expected market return (can take index returns) (3/4)

COC is weighted average of cost of debt & cost of equity (as per CAPM model) i.e.  Cost of Equity (COE) x Weight of equity + Cost of debt (COD) x Weight of debt  Here, we need to understand the concept of cost of equity to get the COC of the co. (2/4)

For finance geeks, what is COST OF CAPITAL? The COC of the company is considered as a hurdle rate in equity investing. It‚Äôs used as a benchmark to gauge the capability of management for creation of shareholders‚Äô wealth. Let‚Äôs understand the concept of COC:- (1/4)
